The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Mumbai: With the 2011 World Cup inching closer, the Board of Control for Cricket in India is trying to rope in Congress general secretary Rahul Gandhi to promote the show-piece event, to be held in the sub-continent.     
	While Vinod Kambli and former India hockey coach Joaquim Carvalho welcomed the move, former world cue-sports champion, Michael Ferrera said that cricket did not need such a high profile personality for its promotion.         
	Calcutta: Air India will meet India Cements in the first semi-final of the BCCI Corporate Trophy, in Visakhapatnam, on Sunday. The second semi-final will feature Indian Oil and Income Tax.         
	Pune: Defending champion Pankaj Advani edged past Dhruv Sitwala to set up a final with Alok Kumar in the IBSF National Billiards Championship, to be played Sunday, at the PYC Hindu Gymkhana.         
	New Delhi: Karun Chandhok Friday became the first racer to drive a Formula One car on the new Korean Grand Prix circuit at Yeongam ,in South Korea.        
	New Delhi: Former women world No. 1 shuttler Mi Zhou of Hong Kong has been suspended for two years for failing a out-of-competition drug test, World Badminton Federation said Saturday. Zhou tested positive for Clenbuterol, a Class 1 Anabolic Agent on the WADA Prohibited List of substances.        
	Calcutta: Bitan Banerjee of Bengal shocked former world U-14 champion Vidit Gujarati of Maharashtra in the sixth and penultimate round to take the sole lead with 5.5 points in the Tea Board of India Chess For Youth Championship at Netaji Indoor Stadium.        
	Mumbai: Supratim Bhattacharjee, a 13-year-old from Bengal, is among 16 sub-junior footballers from across the country who have been selected for a full scholarship programme sponsored by IMG Reliance to study and train in the US.        
	Rosario: Indian eves disastrous hockey World Cup campaign continued as they lost 1-4 to Germany to complete a hattrick of defeats in the tournament.         
	Calcutta: Vivek Dinodia beat Shravan Kaul 11-8, 11-6, 11-7 to win the Under-17 boys event, in the East Zone Inter School Squash tournament, at the Calcutta Racket Club, Saturday.     
	Other winners    
	Under-11: Yash Jalan, Under-13: Krish Kapoor, Under-15: Soham Bathwal                                                                                                                                                      
